pull_request.title: Faster NTT/INVNTT/Basemul
pull_request.body:
This adds the Plantard-based arithmetic described in [1]. 
My goal was to have some reasonably fast C code, but I did not quite get the results I was hoping for. I instead re-implemented it using Arm [ACLE](https://arm-software.github.io/acle/main/acle.html).

There are some differences to the implementation in [1]/pqm4:
 - Arm ACLE does not support `smulwb`, so we have to use `__smlawb(a, b, 0);` (I tried to make gcc issue `smulwb` in a different way, but it seems it simply does not know the instruction - with clang I did succeed however).  
 - Arm ACLE does not support `pkhtb`, so I reimplemented it myself as `#define __pkhtb(a, b) (((uint32_t)a) & 0xFFFF0000) ^ (((b) >> 16) & 0xFFFF)`, but gcc isn't able to issue the correct instruction. It uses `bfc+orr` (With clang I do get `pkhtb` when using that macro). 
 - gcc does not like to spill to the FPU registers here, so the 4 merged layers in the inverse NTT are not optimal. I instead split that into two loops.
 - I have not yet implemented asymmetric multiplication proposed in https://eprint.iacr.org/2021/986.


Here is some stats on the performance on the STM32F407:

| routine           | ref        | [1] / pqm4 | ACLE |
| ------------------- | --------- |---------------- | ------- |
| NTT                 | 33775 |  4483           | 8077 |
| iNTT                | 48207 | 4828            | 8413 |
| basemul         | 14995 | 2449            | 3426 |
| basemul_acc | 16088  | 2833           | 4070 |

Note that the overall performance is still very poor due to the slow Keccak permutation.

You may ask why I would want rewrite that code using ACLE that instead of just pulling in the assembly. Two reasons: (1) I wanted to know how close you can get to handwritten assembly (answer: not very close); (2) the current M4 assembly is known to perform relatively poorly on newer CPUs (e.g., the Cortex-M7) due to scheduling and we are currently working on faster code and I wanted to have some comparison. My expectation is that the compiler will do quite a poor job for the Cortex-M7 as well, but we'll see. 


[1] https://tches.iacr.org/index.php/TCHES/article/view/9833
